2026-05-17 19:49:10 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #9 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_ideal({"code": "# intent: Load the downloaded OMNI2, GOES, and Swarm Alpha density CSVs for wu334 (train) and wu335 (eval). Build VAR(1) on the 16-hour context at the end of OMNI/GOES input window to forecast these input variables forward 4 hours (hourly resolution). Then fit a linear regression mapping the predicted 4-hour input sequences to the observed 4-hour density sequence using train. Predict on eval and compute RMSE over 4-hour forecast window.\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\nfrom sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\nimport json\nimport os\n\n# load paths from manifest\nmanifest_path = os.environ.get('DOWNLOAD_MANIFEST_PATH')\nwith open(manifest_path) as f:\n    manifest = json.load(f)\npath_map = manifest['path_map']\n\nomni_wu334 = path_map['kramabench-astronomy-hard-7/files/STORM-AI/warmup/v2/OMNI2/omni2-wu334-20160824_to_20161023.csv']\ngoes_wu334 = path_map['kramabench-astronomy-hard-7/files/STORM-AI/warmup/v2/GOES/goes-wu334-20160824_to_20161023.csv']\ndensity_wu334 = path_map['kramabench-astronomy-hard-7/files/STORM-AI/warmup/v2/Sat_Density/swarma-wu334-20161023_to_20161026.csv']\n\nomni_wu335 = path_map['kramabench-astronomy-hard-7/files/STORM-AI/warmup/v2/OMNI2/omni2-wu335-20160827_to_20161026.csv']\ngoes_wu335 = path_map['kramabench-astronomy-hard-7/files/STORM-AI/warmup/v2/GOES/goes-wu335-20160827_to_20161026.csv']\ndensity_wu335 = path_map['kramabench-astronomy-hard-7/files/STORM-AI/warmup/v2/Sat_Density/swarma-wu335-20161026_to_20161029.csv']\n\n# read files\nom334 = pd.read_csv(omni_wu334, parse_dates=['Timestamp'])\ngo334 = pd.read_csv(goes_wu334, parse_dates=['Timestamp'])\nden334 = pd.read_csv(density_wu334, parse_dates=['Timestamp'])\n\nom335 = pd.read_csv(omni_wu335, parse_dates=['Timestamp'])\ngo335 = pd.read_csv(goes_wu335, parse_dates=['Timestamp'])\nden335 = pd.read_csv(density_wu335, parse_dates=['Timestamp'])\n\n# select needed columns and resample to hourly for GOES (which is minute cadence) and density (10-min cadence) to hourly mean\n# OMNI is hourly already\nom_cols = ['Timestamp','f10.7_index','Kp_index','Dst_index_nT']\ngo_cols = ['Timestamp','xrsa_flux_observed','xrsb_flux_observed']\nden_col = ['Timestamp','Orbit Mean Density (kg/m^3)']\n\nom334 = om334[om_cols].set_index('Timestamp')\nom335 = om335[om_cols].set_index('Timestamp')\n\n# GOES: minute cadence -> resample to hourly mean\ngo334 = go334[go_cols].set_index('Timestamp').resample('H').mean()\ngo335 = go335[go_cols].set_index('Timestamp').resample('H').mean()\n\n# Density: 10-min -> resample to hourly mean\nden334 = den334[den_col].set_index('Timestamp').resample('H').mean()\nden335 = den335[den_col].set_index('Timestamp').resample('H').mean()\n\nden334.columns = ['density']\nden335.columns = ['density']\n\n# Now align and pick the specific windows described in prompt:\n# Training: OMNI/GOES: 2016-10-22 to 2016-10-23; Density: 2016-10-23 to 2016-10-24\n# Eval: OMNI/GOES: 2016-10-25 to 2016-10-26; Density: 2016-10-29\n\ntrain_omgo_start = pd.Timestamp('2016-10-22')\ntrain_omgo_end = pd.Timestamp('2016-10-23 23:00:00')\ntrain_den_start = pd.Timestamp('2016-10-23')\ntrain_den_end = pd.Timestamp('2016-10-24 23:00:00')\n\n# But prompt says density for training is 2016-10-23 to 2016-10-24 (4-hour forecast window implies we just need next 4 hours after OMNI/GOES end)\n# We'll construct samples by taking the last 16 hours of OMNI/GOES ending at 2016-10-23 23:00 and predict density for next 4 hours (2016-10-24 00:00 to 03:00)\n\n# For train, find OMNI/GOES values covering 16 hours ending at 2016-10-23 23:00\nctx_hours = 16\nfc_hours = 4\n\n# function to get context matrix for a given end timestamp\n\ndef get_context_forecast(omdf, godf, end_ts):\n    # context is the 16 hourly timestamps ending at end_ts (inclusive)\n    idx = pd.date_range(end=end_ts, periods=ctx_hours, freq='H')\n    om_slice = omdf.reindex(idx)\n    go_slice = godf.reindex(idx)\n    # combine\n    X = pd.concat([om_slice, go_slice], axis=1)\n    return X\n\n# For training\nend_train = pd.Timestamp('2016-10-23 23:00:00')\nX_train_ctx = get_context_forecast(om334, go334, end_train)\n# target density times are next 4 hours\ny_train_idx = pd.date_range(start=end_train + pd.Timedelta(hours=1), periods=fc_hours, freq='H')\ny_train = den334.reindex(y_train_idx).squeeze()\n\n# For evaluation\nend_eval = pd.Timestamp('2016-10-26 23:00:00')  # OMNI/GOES window ends 2016-10-26\nX_eval_ctx = get_context_forecast(om335, go335, end_eval)\n# eval density date is 2016-10-29 per prompt; unclear which times — assume we want next 4 hours after end_eval, but prompt says density: 2016-10-29\n# The prompt: wu335 OMNI/GOES: 2016-10-25 to 2016-10-26; Density: 2016-10-29 (single day). It also said windows overlap at single timestamp where OMNI/GOES ends and Density begins.\n# That suggests OMNI/GOES end timestamp corresponds to density start timestamp. So pick density starting immediately after end_eval -> but end_eval is 2016-10-26 23:00, density beginning immediately afterward would be 2016-10-27 00:00, not 2016-10-29.\n# Given ambiguity, instead follow filenames: swarma-wu335-20161026_to_20161029.csv contains density from 2016-10-26 onward. We'll pick the 4 hours immediately after OMNI/GOES end within that file.\n\ny_eval_idx = pd.date_range(start=end_eval + pd.Timedelta(hours=1), periods=fc_hours, freq='H')\ny_eval = den335.reindex(y_eval_idx).squeeze()\n\n# Check for NaNs\nprint('X_train_ctx shape', X_train_ctx.shape)\nprint('y_train shape', y_train.shape)\nprint('X_eval_ctx shape', X_eval_ctx.shape)\nprint('y_eval shape', y_eval.shape)\nprint('y_train nulls', y_train.isnull().sum())\nprint('y_eval nulls', y_eval.isnull().sum())\n\n# Build VAR(1) on multivariate time series of the input variables using the 16-hour context from train only.\n# VAR(1): x_t = A x_{t-1} + c + e. We'll estimate A and c using ordinary least squares on the context series.\n\n# Prepare series for VAR training: use the 16-hour context as the single sequence to fit a VAR(1)\n# We'll stack the three OMNI + two GOES = 5 variables.\nvars_train = X_train_ctx.columns.tolist()\nseries = X_train_ctx.values\n# Need to handle missing values: assume none as per prompt; but check and fill forward if any\nif np.isnan(series).any():\n    series = pd.DataFrame(series, index=X_train_ctx.index, columns=vars_train).fillna(method='ffill').fillna(method='bfill').values\n\n# Build lagged matrices\nY = series[1:,:]  # t\nX = series[:-1,:] # t-1\n# estimate A and c: Y = X A^T + 1*c + E. Solve for A and c via augmented X with ones\nX_aug = np.hstack([X, np.ones((X.shape[0],1))])\n# Solve least squares\ncoef, *_ = np.linalg.lstsq(X_aug, Y, rcond=None)\n# coef shape (k+1, nvars); last row is intercept mapping to each var\nA = coef[:-1,:].T  # nvars x nvars\nc = coef[-1,:]     # intercept (nvars,)\n\n# Now forecast the inputs forward 4 hours starting from last observed context value (series[-1]) using VAR(1)\nx_t = series[-1,:].copy()\npred_inputs = []\nfor h in range(fc_hours):\n    x_tp1 = A.dot(x_t) + c\n    pred_inputs.append(x_tp1)\n    x_t = x_tp1\npred_inputs = np.array(pred_inputs)  # shape (fc_hours, nvars)\n\n# Now create training examples for linear regression: here we have one training example mapping predicted input sequence to observed density sequence.\n# But regression needs multiple samples; however prompt implies using the train dataset (single sample). We'll proceed to fit linear regression on this single sample.\n\n# Flatten predicted input sequence into feature vector\nX_reg_train = pred_inputs.flatten().reshape(1,-1)\n# target is 4 density values -> flatten as vector\ny_reg_train = y_train.values.flatten().reshape(1,-1)\n\n# Fit multivariate linear regression mapping X_reg_train -> y_reg_train. Use linear regression with fit_intercept=